04387nam a22006735i 9780674042377DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222004mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740423777 a10.4159/97806740423772doi  a(DE-B1597)574401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aLC151 ǂb P86 2004eb 7aLAN0100002bisacsh04a302.22441 aPurcell Gates, Victoria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrint Literacy Development :bUniting Cognitive and Social Practice Theories /cVictoria Purcell Gates, Purcell-Gates, Sophie Degener, Erik Jacobson. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tCHAPTER ONE To Learn to Read and Write: Students Who Fail and Succeed -- tCHAPTER TWO The LPALS Study -- tCHAPTER THREE How Does Print Literacy Develop? -- tCHAPTER FOUR Literacy as Social Practice -- tCHAPTER FIVE Print Literacy as Cognitive Skill Development -- tCHAPTER SIX The Seeming Incommensurability of the Social and the Cognitive -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Print Literacy Development through a Widened Lens -- tCHAPTER EIGHT The Course of Print Literacy Development in and out of School -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs literacy a social and cultural practice, or a set of cognitive skills to be learned and applied? Literacy researchers, who have differed sharply on this question, will welcome this book, which is the first to address the critical divide. The authors lucidly explain how we develop our abilities to read and write and offer a unified theory of literacy development that places cognitive development within a sociocultural context of literacy practices. Drawing on research that reveals connections between literacy as it is practiced outside of school and as it is taught in school, the authors argue that students learn to read and write through the knowledge and skills that they bring with them to the classroom as well as from the ways that literacy is practiced in their own different social communities. The authors argue that until literacy development can be understood in this broader way educators will never be able to develop truly effective literacy instruction for the broad range of sociocultural communities served by schools.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Literacy.2bisacsh1 aDegener, Sophie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJacobson, Erik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674042377zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674042377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674042377/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK